===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of washing something.
## {{lb|en|chemistry}} Originally, the [[purifying]] of oils and other substances by emulsification with hot water; now more generally, a thorough [[cleansing]] of a [[precipitate]] or other non-dissolved substance. {{defdate|First attested from around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
## The act of [[washing]] or [[cleansing]] the body, or some part of it, as a [[religious]] [[rite]]. {{defdate|From mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5-6}}</ref>
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1786|author=William Beckford|title=Vathek; an Arabian Tale|passage=Let water be brought to perform my '''ablutions''', and let the pious Fakreddin be called to offer up his prayers with mine.}}
## {{lb|en|literary|or|humorous|usually|in the plural}} [[washing|Washing]] oneself; [[bathing]], cleaning oneself up. {{defdate|From mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1835|author=[[s:Author:William Gilmore Simms|William Gilmore Simms]]|title=[[s:The Partisan|The Partisan]]|publisher=Harper|section=[[s:The Partisan/II|Chapter II]]|page=[[s:Page:The Partisan, v1.djvu/26|25]]|passage=He followed the steps of Bella, who soon conducted him to his chamber, and left him to those '''ablutions''' which a long ride along a sandy road had rendered particularly necessary.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author=J. M. Coetzee|authorlink=J. M. Coetzee|title=Slow Man|year=2005|publisher=Viking|location=New York|page=28|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/slowman0000coet/page/28/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-670-03459-8|chapter=Four|passage=She treats him not as a doddering old fool but as a man hampered in his movements by injury. Patiently, without baby-talk, she helps him through his '''ablutions'''.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|author=Maria Cramer|title=See Fewer People. Take Fewer Showers.|work=The New York Times|date=2021-05-06|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/06/health/shower-bathing-pandemic.html|issn=0362-4331|passage=There are now indications that it has caused some Americans to become more spartan when it comes to '''ablutions'''.}}
## {{lb|en|Western|_|Christianity}} The [[rinse|rinsing]] of the priest's hand and the sacred vessel following the [[Communion]] with, depending on [[rite]], [[water]] or a mix of it and [[wine]], which may then be drunk by the priest. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
# The liquid used in the cleansing or ablution. {{defdate|From early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{RQ:Pope Iliad}}
#*:Cast the '''ablutions''' in the main
# {{lb|en|Eastern Orthodoxy}} The [[ritual]] consumption by the [[deacon]] or priest of [[leftover]] sacred wine of host after the Communion.
# {{lb|en|pluralonly|UK|military}} The location or building where the showers and basins are located. {{defdate|From mid 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

